[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(7) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "The way of the just is uprightness.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The English version seems somewhat tautologous. Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "is straight, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "even",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—i.e., leads on without interruption to its appointed end. So, in the second clause, instead of “thou shalt weigh the path,” which conveys a not very intelligible thought, we render, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "makest smooth the path. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Probably, too, the word translated, “most upright,” as if it were a vocative, should be taken adverbially. The verse is, as it were, an echo of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 4:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 5:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Isaiah 26:7",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 26:7",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The way of the just is uprightness — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "מישׁרים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "righteousness. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The just proceed steadily on in the practice of the various duties of righteousness, which they owe to God and man; or, their way is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "evenness, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "plainness, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "as the word may be rendered. It is their constant care and endeavour to walk with God in an even, steady course of obedience and holy conversation. Bishop Lowth translates the clause, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the way of the righteous is perfectly straight, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "not crooked, involved, and intricate, like that of the wicked. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou, most upright, dost weigh the path of the just ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Dost ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "mark ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "consider ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "it, and observe the various difficulties and dangers that will occur in it, and wilt give them grace sufficient for them; or, thou dost ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "examine it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Thou, who art most upright in all thy ways, and therefore a lover of uprightness, and of all upright men, dost weigh, dost narrowly observe and ponder, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the path of the just; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "the whole course of their actions, and, which is implied, dost approve of them, and direct them to a happy issue. This seems to be the most common meaning of the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "פלס",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", here rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to weigh: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 4:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 5:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It bears, however, another sense, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 78:50",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", namely, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "make the way plain, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or, to remove obstructions out of it. In this sense Bishop Lowth understands it here, and therefore translates the clause, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "thou most exactly levellest the path of the righteous. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "While the way of the wicked is perplexed, and rugged, and full of obstructions, God makes the way of the righteous plain and easy before them, by preventing or removing those things that would be stumbling-blocks to them, so that they walk safely and comfortably forward in the path of duty.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "26:5-11 The way of the just is evenness, a steady course of obedience and holy conversation. And it is their happiness that God makes their way plain and easy. It is our duty, and will be our comfort, to wait for God, to keep up holy desires toward him in the darkest and most discouraging times. Our troubles must never turn us from God; and in the darkest, longest night of affliction, with our souls must we desire him; and this we must wait and pray to him for. We make nothing of our religion, whatever our profession may be, if we do not make heart-work of it. Though we come ever so early, we shall find God ready to receive us. The intention of afflictions is to teach righteousness: blessed is the man whom the Lord thus teaches. But sinners walk contrary to him. They will go on in their evil ways, because they will not consider what a God he is whose laws they persist in despising. Scorners and the secure will shortly feel, what now they will not believe, that it is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God. They will not see the evil of sin; but they shall see. Oh that they would abandon their sins, and turn to the Lord, that he may have mercy upon them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The way of the just is uprightness - The Hebrew is literally, 'The way to the just is uprightness;' the word 'way' probably refers to God's way, or his dealings with the righteous. The sentiment is, that his dealings with them are just; that though they are afflicted and oppressed, yet that his ways are right, and they will yet perceive it. This is language supposed to be used by the captive Jews after they had seen the proud city of Babylon taken, and after God had come forth to restore them to their own land. The word 'uprightness' in the original is in the plural number, but is often used in the sense of straightness ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 23:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Sol 7:10; of sincerity, or uprightness Sol 1:4; or of righteousness as a judge Psa 9:9; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 58:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 99:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Thou most upright - Evidently an address to God, as being most just, and as having now evinced his uprightness in the deliverance of his people. The same epithet is applied to him in Deuteronomy 32:4; Psalm 25:8; Psalm 92:16.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Thou most upright - Evidently an address to God, as being most just, and as having now evinced his uprightness in the deliverance of his people. The same epithet is applied to him in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 32:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 25:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 92:16",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Dost weigh the path of the just - The word used here (פלס  pâlac) may mean to weigh as in a balance Psalm 58:3; but it may also mean, and does usually, to make straight or smooth; to beat a path; to make level Psalm 78:50; Proverbs 4:26; Proverbs 5:21. Here it probably means, that God had made the way smooth, or exactly level. He had removed all obstacles, and had conducted his people in a plain and leveled way (see the notes at Isaiah 40:3-4). ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Dost weigh the path of the just - The word used here (פלס  pâlac) may mean to weigh as in a balance ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 58:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; but it may also mean, and does usually, to make straight or smooth; to beat a path; to make level ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 78:50",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 4:26",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 5:21",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Here it probably means, that God had made the way smooth, or exactly level. He had removed all obstacles, and had conducted his people in a plain and leveled way (see the notes at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 40:3-4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
