  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "7. uprightness—rather, \"is direct,\" that is, is directed by God to a prosperous issue, however many be their afflictions in the meantime (as in the case of the Jewish exiles); the context requires this sense (Ps 34:19; Pr 3:6; 11:5), [Maurer]: thus \"way\" means God's dealings with the righteous (Ps 37:23).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "most upright—(De 32:4).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "dost weigh—(1Sa 2:3; Pr 5:21). Rather, \"thou dost make plain and level\" [Maurer], removing all obstacles (Isa 40:3, 4).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Is uprightness; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "most even or plain",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Heb. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "evenness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "plainness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Which is understood either, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1. Of the rectitude or goodness of his actions or course; or rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2. Of the good success of his affairs; for this suits best with the coherence. When the way of the wicked is rugged, in which they easily stumble and fall into mischief, of which he spoke, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Isaiah 26:5,6",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 26:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ",6",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the path of just men is plain and smooth, and they walk safely and comfortably in it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Thou, most upright, dost weigh the path of the just:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the sense of the words thus rendered is, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", O God, who art ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "most upright",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in all thy ways, and therefore a lover of uprightness. and of all upright men, dost weigh (i.e. examine) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the path of the just",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the course of his actions, and, which is implied, dost approve of them, and therefore direct them to a happy issue. But the words are otherwise rendered by some late learned interpreters, to this purpose, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou dost level",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "make plain",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (as this very word signifies, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Psalm 78:50",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 78:50",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the path of the just exactly, Heb. with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "evenness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or evenly, so as to make it very even. Thus the first clause declares that it was even or plain, and this showeth whence or by whom it is made such, even by God. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The way of the just is uprightness,.... Or, \"the way for the just is uprightnesses\" (s), most upright; the way which is appointed for him, and which he is directed to walk in, is a way of righteousness and holiness, and in which he does walk; he walks uprightly, according to the rules of the word, becoming the Gospel of Christ, and worthy of his calling: or, it is \"evennesses\"; a most plain and even way, in which men, though fools, shall not err, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 35:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or, \"the way\" of the Lord \"to the just is uprightnesses\", or \"evennesses\"; most upright, or most even; there is no inequality in it, though sometimes so charged, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 18:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is entirely agreeable to justice, equity, and truth; regular and even, and suited to all his perfections of wisdom, goodness, &c. (t): ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "thou most upright; these words are addressed to God, and contain an appellation and description of him, who is upright, just, and true, and loves upright and righteous persons; so Kimchi and Ben Melech take the word to be in the vocative case, and as an address to God; though some render them, \"he is upright\" (u); that is, the just man is upright, whose way is uprightness; but the former sense best agrees with what follows: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "dost weigh the path of the just; observe, consider, and approve of it, as being according to rule, and agreeable to his mind and will, Psalm 1:6 or, \"thou dost level\" or \"make even the path of the just\" (w); remove all impediments and obstructions out of it, direct his goings, order his steps, and cause him to walk in a straight way, wherein he shall not stumble, Jeremiah 31:9 and so this is a reason given why the way of the just is even, because it is made so by the Lord himself. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "dost weigh the path of the just; observe, consider, and approve of it, as being according to rule, and agreeable to his mind and will, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 1:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " or, \"thou dost level\" or \"make even the path of the just\" (w); remove all impediments and obstructions out of it, direct his goings, order his steps, and cause him to walk in a straight way, wherein he shall not stumble, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 31:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " and so this is a reason given why the way of the just is even, because it is made so by the Lord himself. ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(s)   \"via justo rectitudines\", Vatablus. (t) For this note, I am indebted to my learned, pious, and ingenious friend, the Rev. Mr. Hervey; see Theron and Aspasio, vol 2. Dialog. 13. p. 225. Ed 3.((u) \"rectus est\", De Dieu. (w) \"aequabis\", Vatablus. So Ben Melech explains it by  making a thing plain and even. ",
        "children": [
          {
