    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The righteous, who go astray according to the judgment of the world, thus arrive at a goal from which their way appears in a very different light. \"The path that the righteous man takes is smoothness; Thou makest the course of the righteous smooth.\" ישׁר is an accusative predicate: Thou rollest it, i.e., Thou smoothest it, so that it is just as if it had been bevelled with a rule, and leads quite straight (on the derivative peles, a level, see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 37:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and without interruption to the desired end. The song has here fallen into the language of a mashal of Solomon (vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 4:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 5:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It pauses here to reflect, as if at the close of a strophe. ",
        "children": []
